I also, have always loved them prayer, “and forgive us our trespasses as we forgive those who trespass against us”.

This isn’t a fit all solution, but it’s a solution that will work most of the time. 

You have a pain body. @eckharttolle describes this main body as the energy within us that’s addicted to staying hurt, angry, and in pain. You can call it the your ego or your trauma. Whatever you label it, it usually looks like blaming others, blaming yourself and lots of guilt and shame for all involved. Many studies show fear, guilt, and shame is an old paradigm of leadership or being in relationship…with anyone…mother child, boyfriend, girlfriend. Guilt and shame is a really long way to go about healing. 

You get to pick your hard and I know first hard forgiveness is difficult for you. You don’t have to think of it as forgiving or letting go, but what if you thought of it as an experiment. The experiment is to look for the strengths in others and things you appreciate in them even if you don’t feel it’s all true. And then communicate this positive attribute to them verbally. 

Some of us have to be the ones in our families who start the healing cycle, even if you’re the child, and especially if you’re an empath. We get to use the gift of love and grace. As a result, you might just experience miracles, shifting in how people show up, a holy instant of healing for all involved. Love is fucking powerful, don’t be stingy with it, regardless of what’s happened in the past. You deserve peace and so do they. 

Not always, but most times. 💞

Let’s nitpick my breakfast! 🍳 (save this for later so you can reference it) 

When putting a meal together I try to: 

1️⃣. Pick a fiber! 
Think fruits or veggies, beans, etc 

2️⃣. Pick a protein 
egg whites, lean deli meats, protein powder. 

3️⃣. Pick a healthy fat! 
Avocado, MCT oil like the one in my coffee creamer (tastes incredible), cheeses, oils nuts. Smaller portions a little goes a long way. Fat is the most nutrient dense macro when it comes to volume. There’s 9 grams of calorie per gram in weight. Whereas carbs and protein provide us 4 grams of calorie per gram. 

4️⃣. Pick a carb! 
This meal wasn’t super carb heavy as I’m just going to be mostly driving today and I might have more carbs before I workout / post work. Fruit is a great option for a carb source especially in the morning if you want something lighter. I love rice cakes for a quick option as well and they come in tons of flavors so it feels like a treat, but they are mostly just ALL carbs and don’t have added fats which we’d rather get from an actually food source than something processed. 

5️⃣. Pick foods and pair foods together that sound yummy to you! Eating healthy gets to be fun and enjoyable 🍈🫶

Are you starting your fitness journey over and aiming to lose 20-30lbs? 

Here are 7 things I would do if I were in your shoes and starting my fitness journey over again:

1. Stop working out: Taking a break from intense workouts can be beneficial for your body, especially if you've been pushing yourself too hard. Try focusing on low-impact exercises like walking or yoga.

2. Hit your step goal of 12,000 steps for two weeks before going back to the gym: Walking is a simple and effective way to get moving and hit your fitness goals. Try hitting your daily step goal before jumping back into your usual gym routine.

3. Write down 7 layers of your WHY: Understanding your motivation and purpose for embarking on a fitness journey can help keep you motivated and focused on your goals. Try to dig deep and write down your reasons for wanting to lose weight.

4. Have any hard convos you've been avoiding in your personal life: Mental health is just as important as physical health. If you've been avoiding any difficult conversations, try to face them head-on. This can help alleviate stress and improve your overall well-being.

5. Figure out your base metabolic rate with the help of an online nutrition expert who won't tell you to restrict yourself or give up pizza: Understanding your body's unique needs and metabolism is crucial for weight loss. Working with a nutrition expert can help you make sustainable changes to your diet.

6. Figure out when and how you will get those 12,000 steps in and how to squeeze that extra walking into your day: Incorporating physical activity into your daily routine can help make it a habit. Try finding creative ways to fit in more movement throughout your day.

7. Deeply accept and love yourself where you are at and trust the process deeply, regardless of what your head may tell you: Remember, fitness is a journey, not a destination. Be kind to yourself and trust the process. With dedication and patience, you can reach your goals.

I’m going to share a quick practice you can take yourself through today to get back on track & back to feeling capable and confident around your goals 🥰 

Grab a pen and paper ✍️ 

1. Write out 3 things you do that you feel are keeping your weight the same or blocking you from making progress 🫶 

Examples: conforming or modeling to the eating behaviors or habits of others, even though it might not match how you desire to eat or be in alignment with YOUR goals 😛 (super easy to do) 

Waking up and eating a bunch of sugary carbs because it’s convenient and makes you feel better in the moment. 

Thinking about working out, but not getting the recommended 200-250 minutes of moderate / vigorous activity per week…but you keep promising yourself you will starting next Monday! 

(Spoiler alert these examples are my own) 

2. Write your if/then statements for each. 

Examples: if I wake up wanting sugary carbs, then I’ll wait 15 minutes and see if I’m still hungry, wait if I’m not, then when I am hungry make a protein forward breaky with some sort of veggie. 

If I’m going out to eat with friends, camping, or in an environment when I can’t choose the food options as well if I were cooking, then I’ll order a lean protein meal that’s veggie based. (Doesn’t mean I can’t indulge sometimes, but if progress is stalled, then fill up on actually food before the processed stuff. This isn’t depriving or restricting). 

3. Set check-ins with yourself! How well did you do last week, did you stick to adherence of whatever plan you’re on? How are you measuring progress, any changes in weight/measurements etc (look for average weight per week over week not just what the scale says today). 

Hope you found these helpful! ❤️

Everything feels overwhelming and confusing because true body composition change is SUCH an individualized process. Eating .8-1 gram of protein per your body weight OR goal body weight is a GREAT place to begin! 

AND if you’re strength training regularly, getting your steps in and getting enough protein but STILL not seeing the changes you’re after 👉 then you might need to be eating more calories overall while keeping your protein up. 

I like to explain metabolism like credit scores 😂 we all have one, and the tiniest things can change our score from month to month 👉 you could be eating 1500 calories and not be giving your muscles enough fuel to set the campfire logs on fire. 

I know you hate to hear it, but honestly if you focus on being really consistent with the small things, then your body composition will CHANGE! 

It’s unsexy but: 
👉 consistently hit your step goal 
👉 strength training and some kind of vigorous activity (I usually suggest 15 minutes of HIIT 1-2x a week for most clients) and then we really focus on the lifting aspect 
👉 eat your protein 
👉 eat 85% real food or more and a variety of fruits, veggies, protein, complex carbs 
👉 drink your water 
👉 sleep 😴
